# Frontend Standards

Frontend development standards and conventions.

## Hard Requirements

- Do: keep frontend focused on UI/state orchestration and API consumption.
- Do: use strong static typing and explicit validation schemas.
- Do not: move backend business logic into frontend components.
- Why: predictable UI boundaries reduce drift and duplicated logic.

## Opinionated Defaults

- Use a component-based architecture with clear data boundaries.
- Use a dedicated server-state caching layer with explicit invalidation.
- Use schema-based validation for user input and payloads.
- Follow `quality-gates.mdc` for lint/type/test thresholds.

## Exceptions

- Prototypes can temporarily relax strict layering when speed is critical, but
  production hardening must restore separation of concerns.
- Generated client code can include verbose types if checked in intentionally.

## Acceptance Checks

- New frontend modules pass strict type checking.
- Data fetching and cache invalidation use consistent query patterns.
- Validation paths exist for user-provided data.

## Examples

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Server-state query hook
export async function loadItems(resourceId: string) {
  const response = await apiClient.get(`/api/v1/resources/${resourceId}/items`);
  return response.items;
}
```

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Schema validation
type ItemInput = { title: string; description?: string };

export function validateItemInput(input: ItemInput): string[] {
  const errors: string[] = [];
  if (!input.title || input.title.trim().length === 0) {
    errors.push('Title is required');
  }
  return errors;
}
```
